What is the Share Market? (Simple Explanation)

A share market is a place where people buy and sell shares (small ownership parts) of companies.

Example

Suppose a company called:

Infosys

is worth ₹100 crore.

The company divides its ownership into many small parts called shares.

If you buy 1 share, you become a small owner of the company.

Simple Analogy

Imagine a pizza 🍕

Whole Pizza = Company

Pizza Slice = Share

If you buy a slice, you own a small part of the pizza.

Similarly, when you buy shares, you own a small part of the company.

How People Make Money
1. Share Price Increases

Example:

Buy Share  = ₹100
Sell Share = ₹150

Profit = ₹50
2. Dividend

Some companies share part of their profits with shareholders.

Example:

You own shares
Company earns profit
Company gives ₹5 per share

This payment is called a dividend.

Why Companies Sell Shares

Companies need money for:

Expansion
New projects
New factories
Hiring employees

Instead of taking loans, they can sell shares to the public.

Where Shares Are Bought and Sold in India?

Main stock exchanges:

National Stock Exchange (NSE)
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE)
Example
You buy 10 shares at ₹200 each

Investment = ₹2,000

After a few months,
Share price = ₹250

Value = ₹2,500

Profit = ₹500
Risk

Share prices can also fall.

Buy at ₹200
Price falls to ₹150

Loss = ₹50 per share

So the share market has both profit and risk.

One-Line Definition

The share market is a marketplace where people buy and sell shares of companies to earn profits from price increases or dividends.

